Short of a length delivery outside off, Gill waits for it, opens up the face of the bat and steers this one through the backward point region to bag a boundary.
On off, blocked.
Another good stroke by Gill. Cummins dishes a back of a length ball outside off, Gill hops, gets on top of the bounce and slams this one through the cover region. Picks up two runs.
On off, Gill defends this one out.
Similar ball as the last delivery. Again, Sharma is solid in his defense. Josh is testing Rohit here well.
Good length and around off, Sharma watchfully blocks this one out.
A back of a length and around off and middle, Sharma misses his stroke and the ball hits him high on the thigh pad. An appeal but no says the umpire.
On off, RS works this to the leg side.
Hazlewood goes for a bouncer this time on middle. Sharma ducks under this one well.
On off, tucked to mid-wicket.
Lovely shot but for no runs. A length delivery, outside off, Gill punches this one to the left of Cummins, who fields this in his followthrough.
On off, SG works this to mid-wicket.
Another length delivery around off, Gill pushes this one back towards Patty.
Two this time. On a length and around off, Gill guides this through the gully region and the batters pick up two runs before the fielder can run in and stop this one.
Back of a length on off, Gill keeps it out well.
Bumper on middle, Gill sits well under this one. Shubman has played these short balls well so far.
Pat Cummins to bowl from the other end. 2-2-0-0 are his figures so far.
On off, pushed to covers.

An appeal for LBW but turned down. A back of a length delivery around off and middle, nips back in after pitching, Rohit looks to play at this but misses to get hit on the thigh pad. An appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Looked to be way too high.
Length and on middle, RS pushes this one back towards Josh.
Angles in another length delivery around off, Rohit blocks this one out solidly off his front foot.
On a good length outside off, Sharma shoulders arms to this one.

BEATEN! Lovelyyyyy! What a delivery from Josh, right after the Tea break! On a length and around off, moves away after taking the deck, Rohit is all squared up as he looks to block but he misses it altogether.

We are back for the final session of the Day. The Indian openers, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill stride out into the middle. The Australian players are out and are spreading out on the field. Josh Hazlewood to start the final session of the Day. Off we go...
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

Alright then! India have continued their good work from session 1 into the second session and will look to finish the Day on a high as well. They will be banking on their openers to stay out there for as long as they can and provide a strong platform for them. Australia, on the other hand, will be rearing to come out and scalp a few wickets before the end of play on Day 2. Which team grabs the last session? Join us for the final session of the Day in a short while.

Indians continued their good work from the first session with the ball into the second session as well. Bumrah started things off as he got rid of Paine and Jadeja and Saini got into the wickets column as well. Jadeja, who was phenomenal with the ball, also ensured that Australia end their batting below 350 runs as his throw got Smith out. Another good show with the ball. The Indian openers, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill then went out and safely negotiated the first nine overs really well.

After the Lunch break, Smith and Paine were the batters out there for Australia. But this partnership did not last long as Bumrah did what he does best, make the ball talk. He removed the Aussie skipper and from them on India kept looking to remove the tail of the Australian batting. Starc slogged a few as well but he could not continue and fell shortly after. Steven Smith made a statement of the highest quality as he smacked his 27th Test ton for the Kangaroos and helped them reach a good total which they would be happy with.

Another session which you would say has gone the way of India. They applied the pressure in the first session and squeezed all the wickets out in the second session and have done well to wrap up the Australian innings for 338 runs. At this point, India would definitely be the happier dressing room.
Length ball around off, Gill prods forward and blocks it solidly towards covers. TEA ON DAY 2!
Back of a length on middle, Gill shuffles and tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Good length around off, Gill pushes this one to the off side.
Back of a length on off, Gill blocks this out back to Cummins.
Bumper now on middle and leg, Gill spots it early and ducks under that one.
Length around off, Gill pushes it towards covers.
On middle, Sharma blocks this out with a straight bat to the bowler.
Around off, Rohit solidly defends this towards the bowler.

BEATEN! What a ball. A length ball around off, straightens after pitching. Rohit looks to play at it but misses and the ball is collected cleanly by Paine. A huge appeal from Paine but no support from any of his teammates. Paine doesn't opt for the review. Rightly so as the replay show clear daylight between bat and ball.
Length around off, Sharma shuffles and defends this one towards mid-wicket region.
A length ball outside off, Rohit shoulders arms to this one.
On a good length around off, Sharma covers his sticks and blocks this solidly.
On off, blocked out. A maiden to start off with by Hazlewood.
Well fielded by Labuschagne at covers. A half-volley, waiting to be hit, outside off, Gill leans into the drive and punches this one towards covers where Marnus dives and stops the ball well.
Well bowled and well blocked as well! A back of a length and around off, Gill blocks this one out.
Another length delivery outside off, Shubman leaves this one nicely.
On a length outside off, Gill leaves it alone.
Patty starts off with a back of a length delivery around off, Gill looks to block this one but the ball nips back and hits him high on the thigh pad.
Pat Cummins is introduced into the attack.
On off, Sharma looks to block this one out but the ball takes the outer half of the bat and goes towards the gully fielder, makes a good stop.

FOUR! Something that you see Rohit do a lot in white ball cricket, but this time he does it against the red ball. A short ball, on middle, Sharma swivel-pulls this one to the deep square leg region and it crosses the ropes after a couple of bounces.
A full ball on off, Rohit digs this one out to the leg side again.
Short of a length and on middle, pushed to the leg side.
A full ball on middle, Rohit clips this one to the leg side but the fielder at square leg does not let the ball beat him.
On a good length on off, Gill nudges this one to the square leg region and picks up a single.
Good running. A length ball around off, Gill prods forward and pushes it towards mid off and takes off for a quick single. Good over this for India and Gill.
Fuller around middle, Gill blocks this out on the off side.
NO BALL AND FOUR! SHOT! Second boundary of the over. A short ball on middle, Gill rocks back and times his pull to perfection towards deep square leg. Starc has overstepped on this delivery.
Back of a length around middle, Gill defends it on the on side.
FOUR! Excellent backfoot punch. A shortish ball outside off, Gill punches it through the covers off the backfoot and gets himself another boundary. Nice positive intent from Gill here.
Length ball around middle, Gill defends it solidly back towards the bowler.
Shortish around middle, Gill defends it towards short leg.
Length around off, Rohit pushes this one towards point and takes off for a single, but returns as his partner says 'No'.
Fuller this time outside off, Rohit lets it be.
Back of a length around off, Rohit defends it on the on side.
On a length around middle, Rohit tickles this towards deep square leg and comes back for the second easily. Nice start this by Rohit.
Length around off, Rohit plays that with soft hands towards gully. Green there dives to his left and saves runs for his team.
FOUR! SHOT! A length ball around off, Rohit lets the ball come to him and then guides it through the gully region to collect his first boundary.
Fuller ball outside off, Gill watches it closely and then shoulders arms to it.
Length outside off, Gill lets it go through to Paine.
On middle, Gill pushes that one through the covers and says a loud 'No' for the single.
Fuller length around off, enticing Gill for the drive, but he is firm in his leave.
Length ball shaping away from Gill, outside off, he leaves that undisturbed.
Back of a length around off, Gill hops and defends it on the off side.
Another length delivery on off, Sharma pushes this one to the mid off region.
Outside off, left alone.
Back of a length and on off, Sharma is solid in his defense.
Outside off, Sharma is not interested in playing at this.
On off, pushed to mid on.
Short of a length and on off, Rohit looks to work on this but he misses and gets hit high on the thigh pad.
Who will partner Starc with the ball? Josh Hazlewood to steam in.

FOUR! What a confident stroke! Just shows you what a good mental state he is in. A length delivery, outside off, Gill leans forward and punches this one through the mid off region and even though Pucovski gives it chase, he is not able to stop it from crossing the ropes.
Back of a length and on off, Gill hops and blocks this one out.
Down the leg side, Shubman hops and looks to tuck it away but misses. Paine collects it cleanly.
Another length delivery outside off, Gill, again is not interested in playing at this.
On a good length outside off, Gill leaves it alone.
Rohit and India are underway! On a good length around leg, Rohit tickles this one to the fine leg region for a single.

We are back for the Indian batting in the first innings. The Australian players stride out into the middle and spread out on the field. The Indian openers, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill walk out and will look to negate all that the Aussie pacers have to throw at them until the Tea break. Mitchell Starc to speed in. Here he comes...

AUSTRALIA HAVE DECLARED WITH A LEAD OF 406 RUNS! The target for India is 407 runs! Still around 40 overs remain in the day's play. Will India take the aggressive approach and go for the kill here or will they take a backseat and play safe. Join us for the final session after this short break.

India's bowling was nothing to talk about as Ashwin and Bumrah both got a wicket each in the session. Ashwin took the prized scalp of Steven Smith as he had him trapped in front and had him sent packing. Siraj and Saini both were carted as runs started to flow. Once the second new ball was taken it was easy for Australian batsmen to go about their stokes. Indian bowlers lost the plot there but just at the stroke of Tea they managed to send Green back.

An entertaining and a fast session comes to an end. Australia came out to bat post Lunch with an intention of going for the declaration. Smith and Green began on that note as Smith departed to Ashwin once again but Green and Paine joined forces as they brought up a 50-run stand. Cameron Green in the process brought up his maiden Test fifty as he seemed to have enjoyed his batting by hitting the pacers over the fence. Until he was undone by Bumrah as he fell just 16 runs short of what could have been a brilliant maiden Test ton.

OUT! CAUGHT! Right at the stroke of Tea Green departs! End of an entertaining knock comes to an end. Bumrah finally has a wicket to his name in the second innings. Bowls a good length ball around off, Green looks to smash that through the off side but ends up getting an inside edge to the keeper. Saha takes it and goes up in an appeal. The umpire raises his finger there. After discussing with the skipper Green takes the review. Replays roll in and there is nothing on the Hot Spot but the Snicko detects a spike when the ball goes past the bat. The on field call stays as Green walks back. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 4!

SIX! WHAT A SHOT! A shortish ball outside off, Green shuffles and pulls this over the ropes at deep square leg. That was a massive hit as it went way over the ropes into the stands. Green now moves onto 84. Can he get his hundred here?
FOUR! SHOT! A full ball on middle and leg, Green clears his front leg and smashes this past the bowler straight down the ground for another boundary. The lead now goes past 400.

Review Time! Green has taken the review there, He is adjudged caught behind. Looks to be out there, Lets see what the replays have to say. Hot Spot shows nothing but the Snicko detects a spike there. An entertaining knock for Green comes to an end.
Beaten! Length ball outside off, Green looks to cut but misses and the ball goes through to Saha.
Bouncer now on middle and leg, Green sits under it.
Short and wide outside off, Paine punches this one through to deep point for a single.

Slight delay in play. There seems to be  an issue near the boundary ropes as the umpires Paul Reiffel and Paul Wilson walk to look what the issue is. Maybe the behaviour of the crowd there is an issue. Not easy to figure out what happened there. A long discussion between umpires and the security ofiicials there. The 4th umpire too is out there and they are taking a look into the matter. The security officials have a conversation with people from the crowd as they ask the one whole group of spectators to leave. All sorted now and we are ready to resume the game.

SIX! Consecutive maximums for Green. A fuller length ball around off, Grren again goes for the slog, this time it doesn't come of the middle of the bat but has enough power to clear the ropes at the long on boundary. Declaration coming up soon? Australia now lead by 395 runs.

SIX! MASSIVE! A length ball in the slot, Green clears his front leg and slogs this one over the long on boundary for his second maximum of the innings. The intent is clear here from Green and Australia. He has been given the license to go for the kill by his skipper.
Outside off, Green punches this one towards deep point and comes back for a brace.
Length outside off, Paine looks to play on the off side, but gets an inside edge towards square leg and they take a run.
On a length around off, pushed towards point for a single.
Length and on off, pushed to covers for a single.
Length around off, pushed towards point for a run to end the over.
Length ball but again down the leg side, Paine looks to tuck that one but misses and the ball goes through to Saha. Bumrah spraying it down the leg too many times here.
Fullish around middle, Paine is solid in his defense.
Length down the leg side, Green works it towards deep square for a run.
BEATEN! What a ball. A length ball around off,  shapes away a little after pitching. Green looks to drive on the up, but the ball misses the outside edge and goes through to Saha.
A bumper outside off, Green ducks under it.
Length and down the leg side , Paine looks to tuck it fine but fails to do so. The keeper does the rest.
Sensible batting from Green! Takes a single after a biggie as he pushes this length delivery around off to point.
SIX! BRUTAL! Length ball on off, Green makes room by coming down the track and then lofts it high and over mid-wicket for a biggie.
Good length and outside off, Green times his drive sweetly but fails to get it past the fielder at covers.
Short of good length outside off, Paine slaps it through cover-point for a single.
Length and outside off, Paine watches it and then makes a leave.
Fuller and down the leg, Green looks to flick but misses and the ball goes through to Saha.

FOUR! Maiden Test Fifty for Cameron Green. A length ball shapes away after pitching, Green looks to play at it with hard hands, but gets an outside edge which flies to the right of Rahane at gully towards the third man boundary. A good knock this by Cameron Green.
Outside off again on a length, Green lets it go.
Now bowls an inswinger on middle and leg, Green looks to flick but gets hit on the pad. A bit of appeal but the ball was sliding down leg.
BEATEN! Lovely stuff from Bumrah. A length ball outside off, shapes away after pitching. Grren looks to push at it but gets beaten all ends up. That ball kept a little low too.
In the channel outside off, left alone by Green.
India finally take the second new ball. Jasprit Bumrah too is back on. 18-4-51-0 for him so far.
Shortish around leg, Green looks to tuck but the ball hits the thigh pad goes towards fine leg. They take a leg bye.
Slight halt in play. Siraj is facing issue with his landing area as the groundsman comes out with the hammer. Taps the surface and it seems we are ready to continue now.
Back of a length around middle, Paine works this towards square leg for a run and gives back the strike to Green.
Length ball on middle, Green tucks this one towards deep mid-wicket for a single. Moves on to 47 now.
Length around middle, Green does well to block it out.

Length ball drifting down the leg side, Paine looks to tuck but gets hit on the pads and the ball races away towards fine leg. They take a couple before the fielder returns the ball back. Leg bye signalled by the umpire.
Length ball around off, played back towards Siraj.
Mohammad Siraj is back on. 22-5-63-1 so far from him.
Similar ball around off, Paine stands tall and blocks this one on the off side.
Back of a length around off, Paine pushes it towards covers, thinks for a run but decides against it.
Fullish around middle, flicked off the inner part of the bat towards mid on for nothing.
On a length around off, Green pushes it towards covers and calls his partner for a quick run.
Length on middle, Green blocks this one out towards mid on.
Shortish around off, Green cuts this away towards gully.
The second new ball is available now. India have not opted for it yet.
On middle, clipped to the leg side this time.

FOUR! Paine settling in nicely! Ashwin tosses one up on leg, Paine gets inside the line and looks to slog it but gets a glove on it as the ball races past the keeper and into the fence at fine leg for a boundary.
On the pads, clipped to mid-wicket.
On middle, Green looks to tuck it to the leg side but gets a leading edge towards cover-point for a single.
On leg, tucked to the leg side this time.
Tossed up outside leg, Paine tries to pat it to the leg side but is beaten there. The keeper too fails to gather it as the batsmen sneak a bye there.

DRINKS! Australia have upped the scoring after the Lunch break as expected. Smith and Green started off well in the first couple of overs. Smith, though was once again out to his nemesis Ashwin for 81 against the run of play. The skipper Paine has joined Green at the crease and the duo have put 50 runs in no time. Australia have increased their lead by 350. Let's see if the declaration is near?
Fullish around middle, flicked towards mid-wicket for nothing.
Length on middle, Green again tucks this one past the fielder at square leg and comes back for a brace. 50 partnership up between these two now.
FOUR! SHOT! Shotish ball around off, Green rocks back and pulls this one behind square on the leg side for a boundary. AUSTRALIA LEAD BY 350 RUNS!
Shortish around off, Green guides it towards gully.
Length outside off, Green pushes this one towards covers.
Starts off with a back of length around middle, blocked towards mid-wicket by Green.
Navdeep Saini is back on. 14-2-47-2 from him so far.

FOUR! This time Paine nails it! Floated on leg, Paine goes for the reverse sweep and gets it off the middle of the bat this time. The ball goes uppishlly through gully and into the fence at third man for a boundary. 250 comes up for Australia!
Another fuller one on leg, Paine pushes it to mid-wicket.
On middle and leg, kept out to the leg side.
Floated on leg, Paine goes for the reverse sweep but get it only as far as point.
Tosed up and a bit quicker too as Paine does well to get his bat down in time.
Tossed up outside off, Green makes some room and looks to go over the off side but he gets an underedge that runs past the stumps towards fine leg for a single.
Fullish just around off, Paine drives this one nicely but the mid on fielder gets around and stops it. Good over this from Bumrah.
Around middle and leg, turned towards mid-wicket for nothing.
Back of a length on middle, Paine stands tall and defends this one back to the bowler.
Length ball on middle, Paine blocks it back towards Bumrah.
Fuller again outside off, pushed to the left of the fielder at cover and takes a run does Green.
Play and a miss. A fuller length ball just around off, Green goes for the drive but only connects with thin air as the ball goes past his outside edge. That was so close to the outside edge.
Floated on off, defended off the back foot this time by Paine.
FOUR! Paine at his best! Flatter and outside off, Paine rocks onto the back foot and cuts it powerfully through cover-point for a boundary.
FOUR! Runs coming thick and fast here for Australia! Full and on off, Paine paddles it fine towards fine leg and the ball goes onto meet the fence at fine leg there.
On off, pushed to silly mid on.
Flatter outside off, Green cuts it through backward point for a single.
Floated on leg, Green clips it off the back foot to the leg side.

FOUR! Consecutive hits! This is delicately played! Length and around off, Paine just pushes at it with soft hands. The ball goes off the outside edge past the gully fielder and into the fence at third man for a boundary.
FOUR! GLORIOUS! Full and slightly overpitched around off, Paine leans into it and then drives it through covers as the ball races to the fence there.
Good length and on off, pushed to covers off the back foot.

Edged and past the slips! Length ball outside off, Paine pushes at it only to get a thick outside edge, Rohit at wide slip goes for the catch but fails to hold onto it. The ball goes to third man for a couple.
Another fuller one on off, Paine pushes it to gully and looks for a run but then aborts.
Length ball on middle, Paine blocks it out off the back foot.
FOUR! Green pushing it on! Floated on the pads, Green skips down a bit and then lofts it towards wide long on for a boundary there.
Flatter on off, punced towards covers off the back foot.
Floated on off and middle, Paine clips it towards long on for a single.
Fuller on off, pushed down the ground to long on for a single.
Tossed up on middle, nudged towards mid-wicket for a single.
Tossed up and following the batsman there, Paine pushes it to mid on.
Length around off, blocked by Green on the leg side.

Just short. A back of a length ball around middle, Green looks to work it on the leg side, but gets a leading edge that falls short of the fielder at covers. Vihari dived forward but the ball fell just short of him at covers.
Length ball around off, Green defends this one on the off side.
Fullish outside off, driven straight to covers.
Play and a miss. A length ball just outside off, Green looks to guide it towards point but the ball straightens and goes past his outside edge through to Saha. Nice ball by Bumrah there.
Fuller ball on middle, Green plays it back to Bumrah.
Jasprit Bumrah comes on now. 15-3-40-0 from him so far.
Darted on leg, clipped to backward square leg for a single.
Fuller one on middle, Green plays it to wide long on for a single.
On off, kept out off the front foot.
Tossed up on off, Green stays on the back foot as he blocks it out.
Floated on off, Green skips down a bit and looks to push it out but the ball hits the pad and goes to the off side.
Tossed up on off, kept out towards mid-wicket.
Length on middle, clipped towards mid-wicket where the fielder dives to his right and stops the ball. Good fielding there.
Length ball around off, Paine punches this one through the covers and comes back for a couple. Vihari from covers chases the ball and returns it back but could not prevent two runs.
Fuller length on middle, Paine prods forward and defends it back to the bowler.
Length around off, pushed towards point for quick single.

FOUR! Nicely played. A length ball around off, Green plays that with soft hands to the left of the fielder at wide first slip,beats him and the ball races away to the third man fence. The key was that he played with soft hands there.
Shortish around middle, Green stands tall and blocks it back to the bowler.
On off and middle, Paine pushes it back to the bowler.
Fuller on leg, flicked through mid-wicket for a couple.
On middle and leg, Paine keeps it out off the back foot.
Flighted on middle and leg, Paine flicks it to the leg side.
Another fuller one on middle, clipped to mid on.
Full and on off, Paine pushes it back to the bowler.
Length ball around off, comes back in after pitching. Green looks to cut but it hits the inner part and goes towards point.
Similar ball around off, defended towards covers.
Shortish around off, Green stands tall and blocks this out.
Back of a length around middle, turned towards mid-wicket for nothing.
Fuller around middle, clipped straight to short mid-wicket.
Length ball around middle, Green looks to turn that one on the leg side but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
Another floated ball on off, Paine watchfully keeps it out once again. A successful over for Ashwin and India there.
On off, Paine keeps it out off the front foot.
Who walks in next? Australian captain Tim Paine is now at the crease.

OUT! LBW! THREE REDS! Just what India wanted and the technology comes to their assistance there. Ashwin bowls a nice tossed up ball around off,  gets it to turn a bit towards Smith. Steven there comes on the front foot to defend but the ball spins past him and raps him flush on the pads. Ashwin appeals and there is a shake of head from the umpire. Rahane signals 'T' immediately. Replays roll in. Firstly it is a fair delivery as Hot Spot does not show bat involved. Snicko comes in and confirms the same. Time for Hawk Eye now. Pitching in line, Impact in Line and Wickets Hitting. Three reds and Smith has to take the long walk back. India would be relieved to see the back of Steven Smith and now would hope to wrap the Australian innings quickly to set up the chase here.
Review Time! India have taken a LBW review against Steven Smith. It is a fair delivery. Nothing on Hot Spot as Snicko too confirms it. Hawk Eye comes in and it is Three Reds!
Flatter on off, punched off the back foot towards covers for a single.
Tossed up on off, pushed back to the bowler by Green.
Tossed up on off, Smith comes to the pitch of the ball and then pushes it to covers for a single.
Fulller length on middle, Green defends this on towards mid on.
Length on middle, flicked towards square leg for a run. The fileder dives and stops the ball but could not prevent the single. Australia now lead by 300 runs.
FOUR! Helped on its way. A fuller ball on the pads, Smith tucks this one fine towards the fine leg boundary. He is now looking to score runs at a good pace.
Length around middle, Green tucks this one towards deep square for another run.
Length on the pads, clipped thorugh deep mid-wicket for a single.
Length around off, defended solidly towards covers by Smith.
Tossed up on leg, tucked towards short leg there.
Another tossed up ball this time on off, Green pushes it to the off side now.
Floated on middle. pushed to the bowler.
Floated on leg, clipped to fine leg for a single.
FOUR! On the charge here! Tossed up on middle, Swith sweeps it towards deep square leg and gets a boundary. 50-run stand comes up between these two.
Full on leg, pushed to mid on.
Who will bowl now? Ashwin to bowl from the other end.
Full on off, kept out off the front foot by Green.
Another fuller one off, clipped towards mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Helped on its way! Full and angled into the pads, Smith flicks it through square leg and gets a boundary now.

SIX! That's gone the distance! Short and on middle, Smith pulls it fine over fine leg and gets a top edge on it. The ball sails over the fence for a biggie. Looks to be the norm of the session though.
Good length and around off, Green pushes to the off side for a single.
Length and on off, pushed to mid on by Green there.

We are all set for the action to start post Lunch. The two Australian batsmen Steven Smith and Cameron Green walk out to the middle. The Indian players too are ready on the field as they take their respective fielding positions. Mohammad Siraj to start the session. 18-4-37-1 for him so far.
... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

Right then! The lead for Australia is 276 runs and they are not done yet. How many more will they add? When will India come out to bat? What will be a match winning score from Australia's point of view? All these answers and many more coming on the other side of this lunch break. Do join us for the second session in a while.

India's bowling was toothless barring a few good overs from Saini where he managed to break the 100-run stand between Smith and Labuschagne by scalping the latter. He further went onto take the wicket of Wade to keep India in the hunt. Ashwin has bowled tirelessly but has failed to get any wickets barring that one wicket he had on Day 3. Siraj and Bumrah have not looked threatening at all as both Smith and Green have managed to play them out. Looks to be another long day in the field for them as they stare at a huge score to chase.

The session began with Smith and his disciple Labuschagne milking runs at will. The latter though was given a life early on in the session and he capitalised by getting to his 10th half ton as well as bringing up another 100-run stand with Smith. Though just when it felt that Labuschagne will continue to get to his three-figure mark he departed edging one behind. Wade as usual was not at his best as he too departed quickly. The highlight was once again Steven Smith. The batting maestro once again brought up his half ton and is all set to breach the three-figure mark for the second time in this Test. Cameron Green has looked solid so far in his stay at the crease as he managed to get 20 runs off 58 balls. This partnership is crucial for Australia as Green can play the attacking game and so can Smith.
Yet another session belongs to Australia in this Test. They have been relentless with the bat as well as the ball though out the 4 days of this Test. India slowing getting out of this Test here.
Full on leg, Green clips it through mid-wicket and gets a single. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 4! AUSTRALIA LEAD BY 276 RUNS!
Tossed up outside off, Green blocks it from within the crease.
Floated on middle and leg, clipped to short fine leg.
On off, kept out off the back foot by Green.
Flatter outside off, Smith slaps it through covers for a single.
Flatter and going down leg, Smith looks to pull it but misses it. Good take there by Saha.
Length ball around off, Green drives this one towards covers and thinks for a run but returns back. Vihari there has a shy at the striker's end but hits Green there and immediately apologizes.

That was close. A fuller length ball around middle and leg, Green looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. Loud appeal from the bowler but nothing from the umpire. Rahane is not interested in taking the review and rightly so as replays show there was some bat there. A good ball this from Siraj.
Fuller length around off, Green prods forward and defends this one towards mid off.
FOUR! Nicely driven. A fullish ball around off, Green lunges forward and drives this past mid off for a boundary. Excellent shot this by Green
Length around middle, flicked towards the fielder at mid-wicket.

We are all set to begin the action on Day 4. The two unbeaten batsmen for Australia, Steven Smith and Marnus Labuschagne walk in to resume their innings. The Indian players too are out on the field and ready to go. Jasprit Bumrah to start the Day 4 for India.

INJURY UPDATE - Ravindra Jadeja has been ruled out of the remainder of this Test as well as the series as he has a fractured and dislocated left thumb.  Rishabh Pant's injury is not that serious so will he come out to keep wickets? No, Wriddhiman Saha will keep wickets but Pant would be available to bat.

Pitch Report - Glenn McGrath says that the pitch has lot of footmarks and the tinge of green has disappeared. Reckons that it's a good batting pitch, but there is a spot in the pitch where the variable bounce comes into the picture, where the Aussie bowlers bowled consistently.

The lead is close to 200 runs and with 8 wickets still, at their disposal, Australia would look to play the attacking game. The question is how many more will Australia add? What score will they feel safe for declaration? For India, wickets are must and they would need that quickly in the morning session. How will the game pan out? We will find out as the session unfolds shortly.

For India, it was all but poor batting, in their first essay, which made them play the catching game for the rest of the day. Only Pujara and Gill managed to get to their 50s and some lower-order hitting by Jadeja ensured that India concedes a lead of less than a hundred. It was Pat Cummins, who rocked India constantly. He finished with a 4-fer and the rest of the bowling unit supported him well.

Coming out to bat for the second time, the hosts though lost a couple of quick wickets, as both their openers were sent packing. Once again the master and his disciple were at work as they added a 68-run stand to see off a successful day for Australia.
The moving day of the 3rd Test between India and Australia at the iconic SCG belonged to the hosts. First they decimated India for 244 runs, taking a lead of 94 runs in the process.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right! That ends the moving day and you can say it has moved well and truly, in Australia's direction. A lead of 197, 8 wickets in the bag and two entire day's play left. You would assume the Aussies have their noses well ahead in this game now. Can India bounce back on Day 4? Or will Australia be able to strengthen their position further in the game? We will find out all these on Day 4. The action will begin on Sunday, 10th January 2021 at 1000 local (2300 GMT, PREVIOUS DAY). Join us for the same then. For now, goodbye and take care!

Cheteshwar Pujara is caught for a quick chat. He says the plan was to build a partnership today and carry on from there, but they lost a couple of wickets that dented them. Also praises Australian bowlers for bowling good lines and lengths. But reckons one needs to spend a long time at the crease and then scoring can become easy. Adds that it does look like a flat wicket but it isn't that easy to score runs. Also says losing Jadeja is a big loss for them, but is hopeful he will be fit for Day 4. Ends by saying that they need to take early wickets on Day 4 to get back in the game.

After that, the Indians bowled well to get rid of the two Aussie openers for a low score but Labuschagne and Smith were in the thick of things again and did exceptionally well to add 50-plus. They didn't let the Indians control things as they scored briskly and kept the scoreboard ticking. They both are unbeaten and have taken Australia towards a very good lead already.

The Aussie bowlers were superb with the ball. It was Cummins who gave them the breakthrough and ended with a 4-fer, picking the last man as well. Cummins, Starc and Hazlewood tested the Indians with sharp bouncers and gave them a few bruises too. Jadeja got hit on his thumb and had to go for the scans during the final session. Overall, it was an excellent bowling performance from the Aussies.

Earlier in the day, the Aussie bowlers tied the Indian overnight batters in the first session. Rahane eventually fell but Pant along with Pujara added 50-plus, with both the batters showing some intent in the middle. However, once Pant was dismissed, it was the case of one following the others. Their three batters were run out and that didn't help their cause one bit. Jadeja hit a few boundaries before Siraj was dismissed, with Australia getting a 94 run lead.

An excellent session for the Aussies. They take the honours of winning the day with superb performance throughout the day. While they have lost two wickets in this session, Labuschagne and Smith have stretched the lead close to 200 already.

That is it from this game. It was a hard-fought game here in Sydney and this further creates an environment for the final Test. There were speculations of the final Test to be played at Sydney only after the Indian team's unwillingness to travel to Brisbane. But everything is sorted out as it is confirmed that the final Test will be played as per schedule at the Woolloongabba in Brisbane on Friday, 15th January 2021. Join us for that at 1000 local (1200 GMT). Till then, take care and cheers!

Australia skipper, Tim Paine says that they created enough chances to go for the win. Mentions that the bowlers bowled well and the dropped catches did not do their cause. He mentions that they are back as a batting unit and the bowlers created opportunities and says that it was a whole-hearted effort from the boys. He says that the young guys coming into the team were just brilliant and they look forward to the Brisbane Test.

India skipper, Ajinkya Rahane says that it was all about character and is really happy with the way they played. Mentions that there are a few things which they need to look at. He says that Rishabh Pant's innings was one of a kind as he played an attacking innings. Praises the efforts of Vihari and Ashwin. Mentions that Pant is fine and injuries are something that they cannot control. On Vihari's availability for the last Test, he mentions that it will be assessed before they take a call for the final Test at Brisbane.

STEVEN SMITH IS NAMED THE MAN OF THE MATCH! He says that it was a hard-fought game. India fought hard as the bowlers kept running into them. Says that the pitch was placid and there was less uneven bounce than they expected. Mentions that a century is always special at his home ground but says that he would have loved it if they had won. Ends by saying that he just absorbed the pressure and just observed the ball and played at it.

India began the chase of 407 on a positive note as Gill and Sharma managed to stitch a 71-run stand for the first wicket. Though Gill departed Sharma got to his first Test fifty as an opener in an overseas Test but he too could not continue as he departed after getting to his milestone. Pujara and Rahane saw of the day for the visitors as they took the game into day 5. Needing 309 runs for victory on Day 5 what unfolded was a sheer cricketing action of the highest level as the game ran down the entire day to end in a stalemate. To know the Man of the Match and captain insights, stay tuned for presentations...

Australia second innings was all about Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith as they once again added a 100-run stand as they both got to their respective fifties. Further to go by Cameron Green's maiden Test fifty and Tim Paine's 39 off 52 balls meant that Australia ended with 312 runs as they declared with a lead of 406 runs. Once again the Indian bowlers were on the receiving end as they were milked for runs. Bumrah and Siraj ended with a wicket each while Saini and Ashwin managed to get  a couple to their name.

India's reply in the first innings started with new opening pair of Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill stitching a 70-run stand. Though Rohit departed, Gill showed his mettle as an international player as he brought his maiden Test fifty. Soon after that, he departed to hand Australia the advantage as they lost two quick wickets. Pant and Pujara steadied the ship for the visitors with a 50-run stand but once Pant departed it was a matter of time as India folded for 244 runs handing Australia a 94-run lead. Some lower-order hitting from Ravindra Jadeja ensured the lead for Australia was well below 100 runs. He though suffered a fracture and a dislocated left thumb after coping a blow from a Starc bumper. For Australia, with the ball, it was Pat Cummins who wreaked havoc in the Indian camp with a 4-fer as Hazlewood managed to get a couple and Starc managed a wicket only.

After winning the toss and opting to bat, Australia began poorly with Warner sent packing but then came the rain and it washed out a majority of the day. Only 55 overs were possible as debutant Will Pucovski and Marnus Labuschagne saw off the day for the hosts. The debutant though ended with a score of fifty on Day 1 to hand the hosts the advantage. Further going into Day 2, Australia found contributions from Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith as the latter got to his 27th Test ton but the former missed out his by just 9 runs. Some lower-order hitting from Starc meant that Australia ended with 338 on the board. The Indian bowling was taken for runs as all the bowlers leaked runs. Ravindra Jadeja was the star for them as he ended with a 4-fer as Ashwin went wicketless. Bumrah and Saini ended with a couple as Siraj had just one to his name.

Day 5 started on the right note for the hosts as they sent the Indian skipper back into the hut early but little did they know of what was going to come their way. Out walked Rishabh Pant and what unleashed was as pure brutal innings from him. He took a special liking to Lyon as he carted him all over the place. His attacking innings helped India gain the momentum going into the second session of the final day. He along with Pujara not only kept the Australian attack at bay but took them out too. Pant got to his half ton and was on course of a well-deserved ton but fell short by 3 runs. Pujara batted the way he does the best as he too notched up his fifty. Just when he was going good playing out the new ball, Hazlewood came in and ended his stay in the middle. Vihari coming in after Pant and with lack of form started nervously before picking out a hamstring injury while going for a run with Pujara at the other end. Since Pujara's dismissal, the game changed completely as they batted out for a draw.

Going into the final session, India needed to play out 35 overs with Vihari and Ashwin unbeaten and 5 wickets in the bag for them. What unfolded was a typical old school style of batting as Vihari and Ashwin managed to keep everything out that was thrown at them. Ashwin though showed a lot of grit and determination as despite taking a lot of blows onto his body he hung around to see India home with a draw. Australia bowling their hearts out there tried everything they could or was in their hand but they failed to breach the defenses of the two Indian batsmen out there. To add to their woes dropped catches added insult to injury as Paine dropped three and Abbott substituting for Will Pucovski dropped Ashwin early in his innings. In the end, India managed to get away with a draw with one Test to play for.

What a Test match we have had! Kudos to Vihari and Ashwin for hanging in there to eke out a draw as the players shake hands with just six balls remaining of the mandatory overs. Special praise for Vihari for showing grit and fight despite suffering a hamstring injury early in his innings. A brilliant 5 days of a Test match, a true entertainment. We have seen rain, run-scoring, collapse, dropped catches, fightback, resilience and what not. Australia would be the most disappointed of the two sides as they let the game slip from the point where they could have had the result in their favour. A moral victory for India going ahead into the final Test.

We are back for the final session of Day 5. The Australian players are out in the middle. Hanuma Vihari and Ravichandran Ashwin will resume the innings for India. Pat Cummins will start the proceedings for this session.
... Day 5, Session 3 ...

So, with 127 runs to win but lack of specialist batsmen might come to hurt India in this Test. Australia just have to do what they do the best. Take wickets and get closer to the win. What will be the final outcome after the final session of the 3rd Test? A win for Australia or a draw. Join us for the final session of this Test in a while.

India did not start well in the session as Pant just fell short of his century which could have been a match winning one but was cut shot by Lyon. Pujara got to his fifty and continued to play the new ball and just when it looked that he would be going on and on, he was castled by a peach of a delivery from Josh Hazlewood. Vihari struggling for form was dealt a blow when he pulled his hamstring while going for a run. Ashwin has so far held the fort as Jadeja's availablity with the bat is still unkown. The tail to follow later so India's hopes on this pair is more.

Australia's session as has been the norm in this Test. What a remarkable session after being pushed on the back foot by Pant in the first session. The hosts started well after the Lunch as they got rid of the attacking Rishabh Pant just before the new ball was due. Then with the new ball they had the run scoring in check as Hazlewood delivered a peach to get rid of Pujara. Since then they have been right on the money. Lyon has found his mojo back as he kept it tight. Starc was also at his best with the new ball and the tail at his disposal. Overall a session which brought back Australia into the game.

We are back for the second session of Day 5. The Australian players are out in the middle. Cheteshwar Pujara and Rishabh Pant will resume their innings for India. Mitchell Starc will start the proceedings for this session.
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

Right then! The game is nicely poised at this stage with India needing 201 runs to get an unlikely win. The key for them here is Rishabh Pant as after him only Vihari is the specialist batsman left. Ashwin can bat a bit but Jadeja being unavailable means that the responsibility falls on the shoulders of the pair of Pujara and Pant. The question is how long can they continue in the same manner? Will Pant and Pujara see India home with a win or will Australia come back stronger and sharper in the second session. Join us for the post Lunch session in about 40 minutes.

The Australian bowlers tried everything from short balls to fuller length balls but to no avail. The wicket of Rahane was the lone success they have had in the session. Lyon was expected to dictate terms but he was taken to the cleaners by Pant as Starc looked off colour in his short spell. Cummins and Hazlewood bowled beautifully as they beat the outside edge of both the batsmen on a number of occassions but failed to scalp either of them.

A brilliant session for India after losing Rahane early in the session. Rishabh Pant came out all guns blazing as he had a liking to Nathan Lyon. He not even spared the pacers as he managed to find a boundary in an over on a regular basis. In the process, he went onto get past his fifty in quick time. Pujara, on the other hand, has been his usual best. Blocking, blocking and blocking. He has held one end up as Pant is taking on the Australian bowlers at the other end. They have also brought up their 100-run stand and look good out there to bat out the day.

Getting Rahane early put Australia slightly ahead in this Test on Day 5 but Rishabh Pant's attacking batting has brought back the momentum in India's favour. Australia would be ruing two dropped chances against the southpaw there off Lyon which came to haunt them later in the session.

We are set to begin the first session of Day 5. The Australian players are out in the middle. Cheteshwar Pujara and Ajinkya Rahane will resume their batting for India. Pat Cummins will start the proceedings for Day 5.

Pitch Report - Ajay Jadeja mentions that there will be some footmarks and that should help the off spinner. Glenn McGrath mentions that it is always a tough one for pacers. There will be some variable bounce on offer and the first session is crucial once again.
Will this game end in a stalemate? Or will Australia go onto take the lead in this series? Stay tuned as the match unfolds in a short while.

Indian batsmen have task in hand on Day 5. On a wearing pitch offering turn and bounce for spin and variable bounce for the pacers. Having 8 wickets and 309 runs more to get an unlikely win, what would be India's approach?

Going into the 5th day, Australia hold all the aces. Having batted brilliantly in both the innings and then with the ball they were just brutal. Exploiting the variable bounce on offer to a good effect. They have set the tone going into the final day. Pat Cummins has lived up to his standard of being the number 1 Test bowler as Hazlewood's accuracy has been pin point. Lyon's tirelessness and Starc's fiery pace has just been too hot to handle for the opposition batsmen.

Wow finally we have a day 5 finish in this Test series. How many of us would have expected it to happen? The build up of this Test series was Steven Smith against India and it finally came to the party in this Test. Hello and welcome to Day 5 of this 3rd Test between Australia and India.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

Right then! Day 4 ends as the game heads to Day 5. First time in this Test series. Australia need 8 wickets while India need 309 runs. Who will take the lead in the series? Or will it end in a stalemate? We will find out on 11th January 2021. The game starts at 1000 local (2300 GMT, Previous Day). Till then cheers and take care.

Earlier in the day, Australia batted for two sessions and gained a lead of 406 runs. Contributions from Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith where they stitched a 100-run stand and later a couple of 50-run stands between Steven Smith and Cameron Green and later Green and Paine saw Australia get to a score of ascendency. The Indian bowling looked toothless and tired as they bowled wayward lines and lengths. Saini, Siraj and Bumrah all were taken for runs as Ashwin the lone spinner in the absence of Ravindra Jadeja bowled his heart out. Saini and Ashwin bagged a couple each whereas, Bumrah and Siraj had a wicket to their name too. In the end, an overburdened Indian bowling attack leaked runs and put India in a precarious situation at the end of day's play.

Australian bowlers were just relentless and unwilling to give up. They started with Starc and Hazlewood and later Cummins and Lyon took over the mantle. Cameron Green too got to bowl after his heroics with the bat. Starc was slightly on the expensive side as Cummins and Hazlewood kept it tight. Lyon asked a lot of questions to the Indian batsmen but failed to get a wicket to his name.

India began the chase in the final session with needing 407 runs for a win. Initially, they began watchfully with Sharma and Gill. Slowly they started to open up as both played their shots. Soon they brought up their 50-run stand for the second time in this Test. Just when it felt that these two will go on and on. Gill departed pegging India slightly on the back foot. Sharma though continued from one end as Pujara found it difficult to negotiate the turn and bounce from Lyon. Rohit, in the end, managed to get to his 50. It was his first overseas Test fifty as an opener. Just when he started to open up playing freely, he holed one out to fine leg. In the end, Pujara and skipper Rahane managed to see off the day for the visitors.

What a day of Test cricket we have had today. The last session seemed to be evenly shared but the day belonged to Australia. They were dominant with the bat as well as the ball. Setting a target of 407 runs for India to get an unlikely win the Australian pacers began on the money as the kept tight line and lengths. In the end, they managed to keep India in check with still 309 runs needed with 8 wickets in hand for the visitors for a victory.

The umpire takes it upstairs as the replays roll in. Rohit looks to be inside the crease when the ball shatters the stumps. Not Out is what the big screen shows as Rohit continues to battle it out.
The umpires have gone upstairs for a run out check. Lets see what the replays have to show.

NOT OUT! Australia lose the review! Gill now survives! Short of good length on off, Gill looks to play at it but is beaten on the inside edge. The ball hits the flap of the pad and goes to the keeper. Appeal from the Aussies but nothing from the umpire. Paine takes the review for a caught behind. Nothing on Hot Spot as the ball passed the bat. A spike on Snicko but it's when the ball hits the pads. No inside edge there. They check for the LBW too, but Ball Tracker shows the ball missing the sticks. The onfield decsion stays.
Review Taken! Australia have taken the review.

Hawk Eye comes in and it is missing the stumps.

Review Time! Rohit is adjudged LBW as he takes the review Let's see what the replays have to say. Hot Spot comes in but nothing on it. Snicko too does not detect an edge. Hawk Eye now comes it and it is missing the wickets.
